    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Forget All You Thought You Knew About Diving]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.ensamiasien.se//blog/2015/10/04/forget-all-you-thought-you-knew-about-diving/"/>
    <updated>2015-10-04T06:13:51+02:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.ensamiasien.se//blog/2015/10/04/forget-all-you-thought-you-knew-about-diving</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>It has been over two weeks since my last update so I figured a new one would be
in place. This time it will be all about diving &lt;3</p>

<!-- more -->


<p>With my buoyancy pretty much under control and over 40 dives I figured I knew
at least the basics about the underwater world (such as turtle&rsquo;s, white/black
tipped sharks, puffer fishes, trigger fishes, nudis, moray eels, etc.). Turns
out that I had seen nothing. Literally nothing compared to what you will see if
you go to
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Komodo_National_Park">Komodo National Park</a>. The
park is huge (total area of 1,733 kmÂ²) and the diving is so diverse that you
wouldn&rsquo;t believe it.</p>

<p>Even though this is a very popular diving destination the
coral reefs are very healthy (and extremely stunning) and the fishes are just
amazing. The visibility is often > 15 meters so you got nothing to complain on
there. If there would be something negative about Komodo National Park it
basically boils down to two things,</p>

<ul>
<li><p>The average temperature is between 26 - 28 which usually means that you would
want to wear a wetsuit. It&rsquo;s really nothing weird with that, it&rsquo;s just that I
usually prefer diving without a suit.</p></li>
<li><p>Some days, at some dive sites, the current can be incredibly strong. Probably
the strongest you ever felt. This can be quite fun, since you get to see a lot
of &ldquo;action&rdquo;, it can also be your worst experience ever. Personally I prefer the
calmer dives, even though I appreciate the experience I get from the &ldquo;crazy,
current dives&rdquo;. <strong>Note</strong>, there is a <strong>big</strong> difference between what I call
<em>&ldquo;a crazy, current dive&rdquo;</em> and a <em>&ldquo;regular, drift dive&rdquo;</em>. <em>&ldquo;Regular drift dives</em>
are fine and usually very cool, <em>"crazy, current dives&rdquo;</em> are, well, <strong>crazy</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>


<p>I stayed with a large group of friends at the newly opened
<a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g1777483-d8449183-Reviews-Scuba_Junkie_Komodo_Beach_Resort-Labuan_Bajo_Flores_East_Nusa_Tenggara.html">Scuba Junkie Komodo Beach Resort</a>
and had a <strong>fantastic</strong> time. The resort is managed by the dive instructors
Rohan and Carys whose professionalism is far beyond anything I&rsquo;ve come
across before. Everything, such as, staff, guidance, equipment, accommodation,
food, etc. is extremely professional. Scuba Junkie really got a good thing going
here, and I will definitely return - <strong>no doubts</strong>.</p>

<p>The initial plan was to do four days of diving
(three dives per day), but after the second day at a dive site called
<em>the couldran</em> I decided, right there and then (seriously, the diving is that
good), to extend my stay and do another four days of diving. Totally I ended up
with 24 dives in the park and a lot of new friends, both under water and above
=)</p>

<p>After Indonesia and Komodo I headed over to the Philippines to meet my friend
Gen for some awesome diving and exploring. Since this is my second time in the
Philippines I pretty much got my route clear on what I want to do this time,
starting off with <strong>wreck diving in Coron</strong>. Before flying out to Coron we
decided to kill a few days in Manila. A city that seems to be misunderstood by
the whole world, at least according to
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Celdran">Carlos Celdran</a>, who is a
performance artist that has very deep knowledge in the history of the
Philippines. If you visit Manila, I definitely recommend he&rsquo;s tour
<a href="http://celdrantours.blogspot.com/">Walk this Way</a> that hopefully will open your
eyes regarding the Philippines and Manila (in particular
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intramuros">Intramuros</a>).</p>

<p><strong>Very excited about Coron and the wreck diving tomorrow</strong></p>

